3.sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade
4.apt list
5.apt-cache policy
6.wget--web get download files from the internet

System Information:-
1.history-->Shows all commands executed by user
2.free-->Free memory of a server
3.cat /prc/meminfo-->memory information
4.cat /prc/cpuinfo-->Cpu Information
5.uanme -a-->Shows System & kernel info (Unix name)
6.du-->Show directoryspace usage
7.whereis--> Show possible location of app
8.which-->Show which app will be run by default 

File Types:-
1.b-->Block File(hard disk, floppy disk)
2.d-->Directory
3.c-->Character File(Keyboard,Mouse)
4.l-->Link file
5.- -->Normal File

File Permissions:-
1.r -->Open the file
2.w -->Writr,edit,append,delete file
3.x -->To run a command/Shell Script
File permissions can be set on files/dir by using thses methods:-
1.Symbolic Method(ugo):-
#chmod [who] [+/-/=] [Permissions] file_name
#chmod u=rwx g=rw o=r file_name
#chmod ugo=rwx filename
---> in changingn of GID and USID
A unique home directory → /home/john
A private group → group john with GID = UID
✅ Makes file permissions simpler and safer (no conflict between users).
#sudo mkdir john
#sudo chown john:john /home/john:- means change owner from root to john
#groups--> shows which groups a user belongs to.(palemupendra adm dialout cdrom floppy sudo audio dip video plugdev users netdev libvirt docker)

2.Absolute Method:-
Instead Symbols using numbers
1.read=4
3.write=2
4.execute=1
#chmod--> Change Mode
#chown-->Change Owner
#chmod 764 <file_name>
#chmod 777 <filename>



File Permissions :-
Permissions Applied in 3 levels:-
1.Owner or User Level
2.Group Level
3.Other Level
Permissions Applied in 3 ways:-
1.r-->Read Only
2.w-->Write/edit/Append/Delete
3.x-->Execute/Run

