File and Directories:-
ls--> list of all files and directories
cat > filename-->create a file and allows to write 
cat filename--> shows content in a file only
cat >> filename--> append content to a previous file that we used file name in command
less--> shows page by page
more--> shows page by page in percent wise
head--> top 10 line in file
head -20 filename--> top 20 lines in a file
tail--> bottom 10 lines in a file
touch--> create 0 bytes of file
nano filename--> create file and allows to write edit               ctrl+o--enter--ctrl+x
vi filename--> create file and allows to write and edit---          esc--enter--:wq
mkdir -->make directory
rmdir-->remove directory
rm -rf-->forcefully remove directory
rm -rf *-->forcefully remove directory not to retake 
tree--> shows visually organized dir,folderas and files

Managing Files or Directories:-
cp-->Copy a file
cp file1 file2--> Copy from source file to destination file
cp file1 dir1-->copy file1 in dir1
mv-->Move a file
mv file1 file3-->means file1 in whole content move in file3, the file1 will disapear(Rename a file)
cd ..--> shift to previous working dir
pwd-->Present working dir
diff--> between two files in content diff will show

Grep Command:- Global Regular Expression Print
This command is used to pick up a particular expression from a file and print as a output
-->grep <patron> file_name
ls -l | grep <patromn>----> list of files in patron will be identify
ls -l | grep ^d-----search a d in list of all files

Sed Command:-
Stream Editor is used to a search a word and replace with another word required to be in the output
Note:-It will be only modify the output , but there will be no changes in original file
1.sed 's/old_text/new_text/' filename
2.sed 's/old_text/new_text/g' filename
3.sed -i 's/old_text/new_text/' filename
4.sed -n '5,10p' filename
5.sed '5,8d' filename

Networking:-
1.hostname-->List hostname of the server
2.ping google.com-->checks the network connection between your Linux system and the Google server.
3.wget-->web get-->download files, software, or packages from the internet directly into your Linux system using the command line.
4.ifconfig-->list IP address(es) of the server /////   ip addr show --> this command also use instead of config
5.telnet localhost 22-->specific port number is working or not.
6.curl-->download, upload, and communicate with web APIs
7.netstat -tulpn = Shows all running network services and their ports, along with which program is using each port.
----> Ping tests connectivity, Telnet tests specific port accessibility, Netstat shows active ports and services. <----

Port Numbers:-
Port numbers        service
  21                 FTP
  22                 SSH
  23                 TELNET
  25                 SMTP
  53                 DNS
  80                 HTT
  443                HTTP

Services:-
Service:- It controls the stopping and starting of services.
chkconfig:-It controls the which service are set to start on boot.
1.service <name of the service> start
2.service <name of the service> stop
3.service <name of the service> status
4.service <name of the service> reload
5.service <name of the service> restart
6.chkconfig --list---> To check the list of services available
7.chkconfig <service> on-->to make the service available after restart
8.chkconfig <service> off-->to make the service unavailable after restart

Archive & Compression:-
1.tar--->(tar archive) archieve files and folders in a single file without compression by default.
-c	Create archive
-v	Verbose (show files while archiving)
-f	Specify archive file name
-z Compress with gzip 
2.tar -cvf backup file22 file4 file55 file55.gz---> archieve these files in backup file
3.tar -cvf backup.tar backup---> archieve backup file in backup.tar file
4.tar -xvf backup---> Extract files from backup file
5. tar -xvf backup.tar---> extract file from backup.tar
6.gzip----> It compresses single files and creates a .gz file, helping save storage space and speed up file transfer.
7. gzip -c file55 > file55.gz---->This command compresses the file file55 and writes the compressed output to a new file named file55.gz, without deleting the original file.
